00:32:14.600 --> 00:32:16.400
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Yeah, of
course, I remember Green Acres.

00:32:16.400 --> 00:32:17.700
&gt;&gt; So hi.

00:32:17.700 --> 00:32:19.000
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Well, hi.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:20.300
Oh wait, is it Susan?

00:32:20.300 --> 00:32:21.600
You're back.

00:32:21.600 --> 00:32:23.070
Oh this is, oh my
god, Susan, hi.

00:32:23.070 --> 00:32:27.790
Wait come up, let
me give you a hug.

00:32:27.790 --> 00:32:30.230
Oop, uh-oh.

00:32:30.230 --> 00:32:33.510
She's my English teacher
from middle school.

00:32:33.510 --> 00:32:42.870
[ Applause and Cheering ]

00:32:42.870 --> 00:32:45.320
And she's talking to my English
teacher from high school,

00:32:45.320 --> 00:32:48.510
Allison right in the
front row, oh my god.

00:32:48.510 --> 00:32:51.100
[ Applause ]

00:32:51.100 --> 00:32:53.020
We'll get a picture
altogether afterwards.

00:32:53.020 --> 00:32:56.390
How amazing, I just saw
Allison in New Hampshire

00:32:56.390 --> 00:32:58.760
and it's-- it was delightful.

00:32:58.760 --> 00:33:04.570
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina: Tom Weld
said you can't go home.

00:33:04.570 --> 00:33:05.870
&gt;&gt; Just--

00:33:05.870 --> 00:33:07.170
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
Do I also know you?

00:33:07.170 --> 00:33:08.470
What's happening?

00:33:08.470 --> 00:33:09.770
&gt;&gt; I'm too old.

00:33:09.770 --> 00:33:15.370
I recently finish reading
"Less" and just before that,

00:33:15.370 --> 00:33:19.320
I had read a book about the
love life of Gore Vidal.

00:33:19.320 --> 00:33:22.050
And it was late-- there's
several books I've read

00:33:22.050 --> 00:33:25.430
about Gore Vidal
and by Gore Vidal.

00:33:25.430 --> 00:33:29.940
And after listening to you, I
have to say, thank goodness,

00:33:29.940 --> 00:33:33.070
you are not going to
wind up my Gore Vidal.

00:33:33.070 --> 00:33:35.070
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
Because he was so bitter.

00:33:35.070 --> 00:33:36.370
&gt;&gt; So bitter and sad.

00:33:36.370 --> 00:33:40.320
And Gore Vidal went though
his life saying he was not gay

00:33:40.320 --> 00:33:45.870
and then he was infuriated if
he was called a gay novelist.

00:33:45.870 --> 00:33:49.800
You know, don't-- it
seems like you don't care

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:52.100
if you're called a gay
novelist, you're just going

00:33:52.100 --> 00:33:54.920
to write what you think
is right for you to write.

00:33:54.920 --> 00:33:58.420
And all I've got to say is
that's the best approach.

00:33:58.420 --> 00:34:02.500
You won't wind up old and bitter
and alone like Gore Vidal.

00:34:02.500 --> 00:34:03.800
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
Thank you [applause].

00:34:03.800 --> 00:34:10.360
But there's still time for
me to do that, but I give--

00:34:10.360 --> 00:34:12.590
for me, I feel like
there was a generation

00:34:12.590 --> 00:34:16.780
of the great male
writers that were all

00:34:16.780 --> 00:34:18.280
in competition with each other.

00:34:18.280 --> 00:34:21.430
And Norman Mailer and
like they all were--

00:34:21.430 --> 00:34:24.350
they didn't seem to have
ended up very happy from it.

00:34:24.350 --> 00:34:25.650
&gt;&gt; No.

00:34:25.650 --> 00:34:27.540
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: And
when I moved to San Francisco,

00:34:27.540 --> 00:34:30.950
there was a community there
of writers who were open

00:34:30.950 --> 00:34:33.060
and generous and
didn't care about rank

00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:38.660
and it was Amy Tan who's here
right now, and Armistead Maupin

00:34:38.660 --> 00:34:42.380
and Michael Chabon and Dave
Eggers and Daniel Handler

00:34:42.380 --> 00:34:48.420
and Khaled Hosseini who were
all supporting each other.

00:34:48.420 --> 00:34:50.070
They were not in
competition at all.

00:34:50.070 --> 00:34:53.760
And that taught me how
writers are supposed

00:34:53.760 --> 00:34:55.100
to be with one another.

00:34:55.100 --> 00:34:58.450
And it is how writers-- I see
them right now like Min Jin Lee

00:34:58.450 --> 00:35:00.580
and I have never met but we
talked on Twitter and we were

00:35:00.580 --> 00:35:02.760
so excited to meet each other
right now because we're fans

00:35:02.760 --> 00:35:05.170
of each other, we're
not in competition

00:35:05.170 --> 00:35:10.770
because she sells way more
books anyway but like--

00:35:10.770 --> 00:35:13.710
I would prefer to be in that
world and there must be another,

00:35:13.710 --> 00:35:15.630
well, but writers
are bitter and angry

00:35:15.630 --> 00:35:17.670
and I don't want
to participate in.

00:35:17.670 --> 00:35:20.820
It doesn't seem like
it mix with books.

00:35:20.820 --> 00:35:22.120
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:35:22.120 --> 00:35:23.920
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
They're better old age.

00:35:23.920 --> 00:35:26.590
[ Applause ]

00:35:26.590 --> 00:35:28.940
And someone's like such a
Pollyanna today, I don't know,

00:35:28.940 --> 00:35:31.840
but I'm just-- I'm in
a very good mood ever

00:35:31.840 --> 00:35:33.140
since April, yeah.

00:35:33.140 --> 00:35:34.440
&gt;&gt; I'm thinking less--

00:35:34.440 --> 00:35:39.960
about "Less", but this question
more I think about a story

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:42.860
of a marriage and a few
of your other books.

00:35:42.860 --> 00:35:45.720
But, when you're writing
from the perspective

00:35:45.720 --> 00:35:48.290
of a character who's not
very much like yourself,

00:35:48.290 --> 00:35:50.340
how do you get into
that mindset?

00:35:50.340 --> 00:35:52.370
And is that a challenge for you

00:35:52.370 --> 00:35:57.700
or how do you go
about doing that?

00:35:57.700 --> 00:36:00.290
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Well,
to me, I feel like it's my job

00:36:00.290 --> 00:36:03.260
to write about people
not like myself.

00:36:03.260 --> 00:36:07.960
It feels like that that fiction
is to try to have empathy

00:36:07.960 --> 00:36:12.000
for people especially
people you disagree with.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:15.210
But also to represent
other people in the world

00:36:15.210 --> 00:36:18.540
that you see with diligence.

00:36:18.540 --> 00:36:22.990
And that means a lot of thought.

00:36:22.990 --> 00:36:24.290
And one thing you're touching

00:36:24.290 --> 00:36:27.120
on is something that's a touchy
topic right now among novelist

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:28.990
which is about representation
of people

00:36:28.990 --> 00:36:32.140
who are different
racial ethnic groups

00:36:32.140 --> 00:36:35.550
that like how do we
dare represent them.

00:36:35.550 --> 00:36:40.600
And I think it's a conversation
that is not over yet.

00:36:40.600 --> 00:36:46.700
But, certainly, it calls upon
us to be basically decent people

00:36:46.700 --> 00:36:50.820
and good writers like you're
supposed to write real people

00:36:50.820 --> 00:36:56.730
who come alive on the page and
that the reader connects with

00:36:56.730 --> 00:37:01.630
and sees their flaws and their
good points like a person.

00:37:01.630 --> 00:37:03.280
That's the job as a writer.

00:37:03.280 --> 00:37:06.190
And so, anyone who just dashes
off like I'm going to put

00:37:06.190 --> 00:37:10.180
in a sassy drag queen waiter,

00:37:10.180 --> 00:37:12.470
like you haven't thought
about long enough.

00:37:12.470 --> 00:37:15.000
But that's just your job anyway,
like you should be thinking

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.690
about the characters
more than the metaphors.

00:37:17.690 --> 00:37:21.920
But I think it's sloppy to--
but-- so I think really hard.

00:37:21.920 --> 00:37:25.130
Like this book I really lost
a lot of sleep putting my--

00:37:25.130 --> 00:37:29.600
sending my character to other
countries, like a lot of sleep.

00:37:29.600 --> 00:37:31.930
And so I just try to
be really diligent

00:37:31.930 --> 00:37:34.760
and not making any
character like a throwaway

00:37:34.760 --> 00:37:38.220
because I wouldn't want to
have throwaway human being,

00:37:38.220 --> 00:37:43.700
so I just-- anxiety and doubt
helps you make characters maybe.

00:37:43.700 --> 00:37:45.990
Does that answer it?

00:37:45.990 --> 00:37:47.290
&gt;&gt; Yeah, yeah.

00:37:47.290 --> 00:37:48.590
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Yeah.

00:37:48.590 --> 00:37:49.890
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:37:49.890 --> 00:37:51.190
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
Thank you for asking that.

00:37:51.190 --> 00:37:52.490
&gt;&gt; Alex: Hi.

00:37:52.490 --> 00:37:53.800
My name is Alex and I also
went to college in Montana

00:37:53.800 --> 00:37:55.100
and that's when I was--

00:37:55.100 --> 00:37:56.400
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
Yeah, where did you go?

00:37:56.400 --> 00:37:57.700
&gt;&gt; Alex: Montana State.

00:37:57.700 --> 00:37:59.000
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Awesome.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:00.300
&gt;&gt; Alex: So-- yeah, but I spend
a lot of time in Missoula.

00:38:00.300 --> 00:38:01.600
And it's not always the
place, we have like a lot

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:03.240
of drag branches
or rainbow flags.

00:38:03.240 --> 00:38:05.220
So I'm wondering if any
of your experiences going

00:38:05.220 --> 00:38:07.740
to school there made it
into this book, and if not,

00:38:07.740 --> 00:38:09.670
how living in Montana
kind of impacted you

00:38:09.670 --> 00:38:10.970
as a developing writer?

00:38:10.970 --> 00:38:12.270
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: This is--

00:38:12.270 --> 00:38:13.570
No one's ever asked
me this before.

00:38:13.570 --> 00:38:15.800
I went to graduate school at
the University of Montana,

00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:18.500
in Missoula, Montana
for a few years.

00:38:18.500 --> 00:38:21.700
And it was a great experience.

00:38:21.700 --> 00:38:23.060
But it was strange.

00:38:23.060 --> 00:38:24.820
I remember people
would say to me,

00:38:24.820 --> 00:38:27.770
I've never met a
gay person before.

00:38:27.770 --> 00:38:29.390
What's it like?

00:38:29.390 --> 00:38:31.710
[ Laughter ]

00:38:31.710 --> 00:38:34.280
And I had just move from
the West Village which was

00:38:34.280 --> 00:38:36.690
at that point, the gay part
of New York and I'm going

00:38:36.690 --> 00:38:37.990
to be like, what's it like?

00:38:37.990 --> 00:38:41.530
I don't know, it's great
and terrible and what's it

00:38:41.530 --> 00:38:42.830
like for you, and I'm just--

00:38:42.830 --> 00:38:45.060
yeah, I get different
experience.

00:38:45.060 --> 00:38:48.300
Or I did-- I mean this will
sound familiar that like,

00:38:48.300 --> 00:38:51.220
you know, like one morning,
I had to word fags keyed

00:38:51.220 --> 00:38:54.010
in to the front of my car.

00:38:54.010 --> 00:38:56.790
And more upset than me
were my straight friends

00:38:56.790 --> 00:39:00.860
who had never seen this before
and like sanded it off all day

00:39:00.860 --> 00:39:03.970
for me and they were to get
back and I'm like, it's like,

00:39:03.970 --> 00:39:07.730
it's not OK but like
it's a shitty car anyway.

00:39:07.730 --> 00:39:10.760
So thank you for
sanding it down.

00:39:10.760 --> 00:39:15.690
But I had to learn in Montana.

00:39:15.690 --> 00:39:22.410
You're not going to believe it
how to butch it up a little bit

00:39:22.410 --> 00:39:26.360
in like a bar like [inaudible]
bar which was a tough one.

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:28.130
And which was funny
to see that I could

00:39:28.130 --> 00:39:31.040
if I bought the right
clothes, I can totally pass

00:39:31.040 --> 00:39:35.460
and like play pool and things.

00:39:35.460 --> 00:39:38.440
And it was interesting to
see that I didn't have to be

00:39:38.440 --> 00:39:42.690
in like a bubble of a ghetto
like the West Village was

00:39:42.690 --> 00:39:47.290
to find people-- actually, I was
with other writers and I felt

00:39:47.290 --> 00:39:49.140
like I had more in
common with them

00:39:49.140 --> 00:39:52.770
than I did the man I was meeting
in the bars in the West Village.

00:39:52.770 --> 00:39:56.010
And in Montana, people who were
willing to take me out camping

00:39:56.010 --> 00:40:00.100
and who were adventurous and
open minded and explorative,

00:40:00.100 --> 00:40:03.310
and I felt like I
found my people there.

00:40:03.310 --> 00:40:06.810
Weirdly, even though it
wasn't easy to be openly gay,

00:40:06.810 --> 00:40:09.580
it was easy to be yourself
in a different way.

00:40:09.580 --> 00:40:12.800
So, I loved it.

00:40:12.800 --> 00:40:14.940
Do you like DC better?

00:40:14.940 --> 00:40:19.350
&gt;&gt; There's a lot more men
here, so that's great.

00:40:19.350 --> 00:40:20.650
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Yeah.

00:40:20.650 --> 00:40:25.140
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much.

00:40:25.140 --> 00:40:37.070
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Yeah,
the food was terrible though,

00:40:37.070 --> 00:40:41.010
I always hear that, you know.

00:40:41.010 --> 00:40:42.310
[ Laughter ]

00:40:42.310 --> 00:40:43.610
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina: We have
one question on this side.

00:40:43.610 --> 00:40:45.230
&gt;&gt; Yes, I'm a middle age woman,

00:40:45.230 --> 00:40:47.740
if I plan to live
to be over a 120.

00:40:47.740 --> 00:40:49.040
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Yeah!

00:40:49.040 --> 00:40:50.340
&gt;&gt; So I just want to say that as
an older-than-middle-age black

00:40:50.340 --> 00:40:51.640
woman, I absolutely
love that book.

00:40:51.640 --> 00:40:52.940
I loved every moment of it and
there's a certain universality

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:54.240
to it that was wonderful.

00:40:54.240 --> 00:40:55.540
I read it and I spoke to my
husband who also would have

00:40:55.540 --> 00:40:56.840
to live to be 140 to
be middle age now.

00:40:56.840 --> 00:40:58.140
And he was so happy for me.

00:40:58.140 --> 00:40:59.440
So when I was getting
ready to come today,

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:00.740
he was so excited for me.

00:41:00.740 --> 00:41:02.040
And I just wanted to kind
of share that with you.

00:41:02.040 --> 00:41:03.340
So that's my little gift.

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:04.640
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
Thank you so much.

00:41:04.640 --> 00:41:06.320
[ Applause ]

00:41:06.320 --> 00:41:07.620
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina: Andrew,

00:41:07.620 --> 00:41:08.920
do you think you could
have read this book

00:41:08.920 --> 00:41:10.220
like maybe 10 years
ago, 20 years ago

00:41:10.220 --> 00:41:14.060
or do you think the tone
of the country helps?

00:41:15.300 --> 00:41:16.600
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Well now,

00:41:16.600 --> 00:41:20.770
I finished the book
before 2016 but as--

00:41:20.770 --> 00:41:22.080
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina: Not
today's country, yeah.

00:41:22.080 --> 00:41:23.850
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: But that
doesn't mean I didn't feel the

00:41:23.850 --> 00:41:27.300
tone of the country
and I think what--

00:41:27.300 --> 00:41:30.210
I didn't know then that
people have told me was

00:41:30.210 --> 00:41:37.440
that they needed to read
a book that was, I guess,

00:41:37.440 --> 00:41:42.040
uplifting without lying to
them about the way things are.

00:41:42.040 --> 00:41:46.090
And I deserve that for myself.

00:41:46.090 --> 00:41:48.740
And I can't tell you what it
means to have written something

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:52.920
like that and to have
people write me and say,

00:41:52.920 --> 00:41:55.520
people tell me how humane it is.

00:41:55.520 --> 00:41:58.510
And I-- that's the best
complement to me when they say

00:41:58.510 --> 00:42:02.130
that they've sort of felt
good about other people.

00:42:02.130 --> 00:42:04.300
And I don't really know how
that happens from that book,

00:42:04.300 --> 00:42:07.640
but I feel like I can
take credit for it.

00:42:07.640 --> 00:42:11.980
I think people are in such a
bad way right now and what--

00:42:11.980 --> 00:42:16.070
you pick up the news everyday
and you say, God damn it.

00:42:16.070 --> 00:42:18.400
That, you could go to
something that feels

00:42:18.400 --> 00:42:22.210
like maybe reminds you of what
you would really like to be.

00:42:22.210 --> 00:42:25.480
I don't know how
to talk about that.

00:42:25.480 --> 00:42:27.840
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina: You've
got a little life shirt on.

00:42:27.840 --> 00:42:29.140
&gt;&gt; I sure do.

00:42:29.140 --> 00:42:30.440
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
Oh yeah you do.

00:42:30.440 --> 00:42:31.740
&gt;&gt; Is that OK?

00:42:31.740 --> 00:42:33.040
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina: Oh yes.

00:42:33.040 --> 00:42:34.340
&gt;&gt; It don't make
"Less" shirts though.

00:42:34.340 --> 00:42:35.640
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina: OK,
we'll take your question.

00:42:35.640 --> 00:42:36.940
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
I should do that.

00:42:36.940 --> 00:42:38.240
&gt;&gt; So I've really love
the way the last--

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:39.780
the book end especially the
last word of bucket, so smart--

00:42:39.780 --> 00:42:41.080
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
Don't give it away though.

00:42:41.080 --> 00:42:43.850
&gt;&gt; So, I'm not giving-- I
didn't say the word but I wanted

00:42:43.850 --> 00:42:46.980
to know when in the writing
process you knew how you wanted

00:42:46.980 --> 00:42:48.890
to end it and how you wanted--

00:42:48.890 --> 00:42:50.550
the specific words
choices you've used

00:42:50.550 --> 00:42:51.850
for the ending to be used.

00:42:51.850 --> 00:42:53.160
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Now, this
is a kind of question readers--

00:42:53.160 --> 00:42:55.360
writers really like and
readers are very bored

00:42:55.360 --> 00:42:58.960
by which is a technical
question about language

00:42:58.960 --> 00:43:01.250
because we spent a lot of time
on it and then we spend a lot

00:43:01.250 --> 00:43:02.730
of time trying for you not

00:43:02.730 --> 00:43:05.690
to notice we spent
all the time on it.

00:43:05.690 --> 00:43:07.330
But I will say that
I wanted it to--

00:43:07.330 --> 00:43:10.350
now it's going to give
away that I wanted--

00:43:10.350 --> 00:43:14.010
it won't give away to
the audience but you--

00:43:14.010 --> 00:43:19.290
I wanted to joke on the
ending of Joyce's Ulysses,

00:43:19.290 --> 00:43:22.350
and the way Molly
Bloom's speech ends there.

00:43:22.350 --> 00:43:26.450
And that's kind of-- I based
the rhythm of it all on that.

00:43:26.450 --> 00:43:28.300
And I thought is
this just too much?

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:29.600
Can I really do this?

00:43:29.600 --> 00:43:32.940
But my editor didn't stop me
and I'm like, I'm just going

00:43:32.940 --> 00:43:34.630
to publish it that way.

00:43:34.630 --> 00:43:37.680
Because I just thought it would
over the top but like knowing

00:43:37.680 --> 00:43:40.980
that it's a little
absurd and-- why not?

00:43:40.980 --> 00:43:42.280
Yeah.

00:43:42.280 --> 00:43:43.580
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:43:43.580 --> 00:43:44.880
&gt;&gt; Rowell Encina: Yeah,
we'll take this side.

00:43:44.880 --> 00:43:47.380
&gt;&gt; Hi, I'm a public
librarian locally

00:43:47.380 --> 00:43:49.010
and I've always wanted to--

00:43:49.010 --> 00:43:50.990
[ Applause and Cheering ]

00:43:50.990 --> 00:43:53.310
-- hope my mother
will be so pleased

00:43:53.310 --> 00:43:55.540
with this applause right now.

00:43:55.540 --> 00:43:57.090
I've always wanted to
share with an author,

00:43:57.090 --> 00:44:00.030
you see how your book
sales and everything.

00:44:00.030 --> 00:44:02.870
But I was lucky enough to pick
up your book right when it came

00:44:02.870 --> 00:44:05.060
in because I can see
clearly just kind

00:44:05.060 --> 00:44:06.620
of take it home before
it gets processed.

00:44:06.620 --> 00:44:08.500
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
You can't do that.

00:44:08.500 --> 00:44:11.460
&gt;&gt; But you see your book sales
but I have not seen your book

00:44:11.460 --> 00:44:14.850
on our shelf and it has over
200 holds on it countywide.

00:44:14.850 --> 00:44:17.320
We own about a hundred
copies and we keep having

00:44:17.320 --> 00:44:18.910
to buy more and more and more.

00:44:18.910 --> 00:44:21.310
We just got our large
type print in--

00:44:21.310 --> 00:44:23.260
of your book and I don't
know that you see those--

00:44:23.260 --> 00:44:25.300
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: I haven't
seen the large type-- oh my god.

00:44:25.300 --> 00:44:26.820
&gt;&gt; It looks the same but bigger.

00:44:26.820 --> 00:44:28.120
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: OK.

00:44:28.120 --> 00:44:31.960
&gt;&gt; So I don't know that authors
ever learn that, but it's you,

00:44:31.960 --> 00:44:34.400
people who are not
purchasing your book.

00:44:34.400 --> 00:44:40.270
That is how there still over
200 people on hold for it.

00:44:40.270 --> 00:44:43.070
So thank you.

00:44:43.070 --> 00:44:44.370
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Thank you.

00:44:44.370 --> 00:44:48.850
&gt;&gt; I felt-- after reading
your book, it was lovely.

00:44:48.850 --> 00:44:58.380
But I felt lovely after
finishing your book.

00:44:58.380 --> 00:44:59.680
So thank you.

00:44:59.680 --> 00:45:00.980
&gt;&gt; Rowell Encina: Thank you.

00:45:00.980 --> 00:45:04.060
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Wow, a
librarian, ladies and gentlemen.

00:45:04.060 --> 00:45:06.670
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina: We'll
take one last question.

00:45:06.670 --> 00:45:09.880
&gt;&gt; Hi, just another
word nerd question.

00:45:09.880 --> 00:45:11.950
Why did you choose the word--

00:45:11.950 --> 00:45:17.850
the name "Less" and were there
any other names or adjectives

00:45:17.850 --> 00:45:25.280
that you had considered
for naming a character?

00:45:25.280 --> 00:45:29.060
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: I never
considered another name for--

00:45:29.060 --> 00:45:35.390
It was mostly-- now it seems
like it's maybe a little too

00:45:35.390 --> 00:45:39.330
on the nose but at that
time, it was to remind myself

00:45:39.330 --> 00:45:46.870
that I was trying to torture the
character and produce his ego

00:45:46.870 --> 00:45:51.440
and his stature so
I could get him.

00:45:51.440 --> 00:45:57.550
Because I thought-- it's very
hard to write a funny book

00:45:57.550 --> 00:46:01.820
about someone except
if you sort of--

00:46:01.820 --> 00:46:05.780
you have to take everything
away to give it back to them.

00:46:05.780 --> 00:46:11.250
Because the other thing about a
funny book is, you have to kind

00:46:11.250 --> 00:46:16.800
of know from the beginning that
it's going to turn out all right

00:46:16.800 --> 00:46:21.720
because otherwise it's
sort of a cruel book.

00:46:21.720 --> 00:46:24.910
So-- And then I just--
the name stuck with me

00:46:24.910 --> 00:46:29.790
and no one stopped
me so, again, yeah.

00:46:29.790 --> 00:46:35.710
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina: We'll
squeeze in one quick question?

00:46:35.710 --> 00:46:37.010
&gt;&gt; Hi.

00:46:37.010 --> 00:46:38.310
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Hi.

00:46:38.310 --> 00:46:39.610
&gt;&gt; So "Less" was
really enjoyable to read

00:46:39.610 --> 00:46:43.560
and like many people in the
audience, we want to read more.

00:46:43.560 --> 00:46:46.840
So are there titles that you
can recommend the same vain

00:46:46.840 --> 00:46:50.060
as "Less" that are
near and dear to you?

00:46:50.060 --> 00:46:51.850
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Oh
well, that's a good question.

00:46:51.850 --> 00:46:56.090
The same vain gives you the
same kind of feeling like--

00:46:56.090 --> 00:46:57.390
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:46:57.390 --> 00:46:58.690
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Because
there's other comic novels

00:46:58.690 --> 00:47:01.660
recently like Paul
Beatty's the "Sellout".

00:47:01.660 --> 00:47:07.520
I think Lorrie Moore who was
here somewhere is the funniest

00:47:07.520 --> 00:47:08.820
writer I know.

00:47:08.820 --> 00:47:10.380
Also there are sad funny stories
but she's a master of them.

00:47:10.380 --> 00:47:14.480
And I was reading, I think
"Pnin" is funny but it's cruel.

00:47:14.480 --> 00:47:15.780
[Inaudible] books
are very funny.

00:47:15.780 --> 00:47:17.920
Weirdly, I've been reading
Graham Greene books recently

00:47:17.920 --> 00:47:19.220
because on my next
book I'm hoping

00:47:19.220 --> 00:47:20.520
to make also a comic novel.

00:47:20.520 --> 00:47:21.820
"Travels with my Aunt",
I find to be a book

00:47:21.820 --> 00:47:23.120
that makes me feel really
wonderful about life.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:24.420
And we don't think of
Graham Greene doing that

00:47:24.420 --> 00:47:25.720
but I think he did
it in that book.

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:27.020
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:47:27.020 --> 00:47:28.320
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Yeah.

00:47:28.320 --> 00:47:29.620
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encima: I'll
ask the last question.

00:47:29.620 --> 00:47:30.920
So, you said you're 47, any
big plans when you turn 50?

00:47:30.920 --> 00:47:32.220
A friend of mine gave me
an idea to have a party

00:47:32.220 --> 00:47:33.520
at different country
or different city

00:47:33.520 --> 00:47:34.820
for each decade of my life, so.

00:47:34.820 --> 00:47:36.120
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:37.420
Oh I thought your friend
had an idea for my party.

00:47:37.420 --> 00:47:38.720
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encima: Oh yeah.

00:47:38.720 --> 00:47:40.020
Well, there's that.

00:47:40.020 --> 00:47:41.320
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: Oh we
could, when do you turn 50?

00:47:41.320 --> 00:47:42.620
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encima: I don't want

00:47:42.620 --> 00:47:43.920
to share it with
like 500 people.

00:47:43.920 --> 00:47:45.220
Like in two years
when I turn 50.

00:47:45.220 --> 00:47:46.520
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer: So close.

00:47:46.520 --> 00:47:47.820
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encima: Yes.

00:47:47.820 --> 00:47:49.120
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
Were-- it's very close.

00:47:49.120 --> 00:47:50.420
I've got-- don't know.

00:47:50.420 --> 00:47:51.720
I've been to a lot of
50th birthday parties,

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:53.020
and the first friend who've--
turns 50, you like flight it

00:47:53.020 --> 00:47:54.320
to loom and you're in
an island and you're--

00:47:54.320 --> 00:47:55.620
get drunk and, you
know, there's costumes.

00:47:55.620 --> 00:47:56.920
And then eventually, people
like meet me at the bar at 6.

00:47:56.920 --> 00:47:58.220
[ Laughter ]

00:47:58.220 --> 00:47:59.520
So I think I'm like
the last one.

00:47:59.520 --> 00:48:00.820
So it'll be more
like that maybe.

00:48:00.820 --> 00:48:02.120
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encima: Oh.

00:48:02.120 --> 00:48:03.420
&gt;&gt; Andrew Sean Greer:
No it won't--

00:48:03.420 --> 00:48:04.720
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encima: No,
it's going to be fun.

00:48:04.720 --> 00:48:06.020
Well, thank you everyone.

00:48:06.020 --> 00:48:07.320
I hope you go see
Andrew downstairs.

